  "prompt": "Any good books to develop a statistical background? For a math major wanting to get more into stats",
  "response": "Here are some recommended books for developing a strong statistical background:\n\n1. Introductory Level:\n- \"Statistics\" by David Freedman\n- \"Practical Statistics for Data Scientists\" by Peter Bruce\n- \"OpenIntro Statistics\" by David Diez, Christopher Barr, and Mine \u00c7etinkaya-Rundel\n\n2. Intermediate Level:\n- \"Introduction to Statistical Learning\" by Gareth James et al.\n- \"All of Statistics\" by Larry Wasserman\n- \"Statistical Inference\" by George Casella and Roger Berger\n\n3. Mathematical Statistics:\n- \"Mathematical Statistics with Applications\" by Dennis Wackerly\n- \"Probability and Statistical Inference\" by Robert Hogg\n- \"Theory of Statistics\" by Mark Miller\n\n4. Advanced/Theoretical:\n- \"Probability Theory\" by Achim Klenke\n- \"Advanced Statistical Methods\" by Geert Molenberghs\n- \"Mathematical Statistics: Basic Ideas and Selected Topics\" by Peter Bickel\n\n5. Applied/Data Science Oriented:\n- \"Elements of Statistical Learning\" by Trevor Hastie\n- \"Data Science from Scratch\" by Joel Grus\n\nRecommended order: Start with introductory, then move to mathematical and intermediate levels.\n\nThese books cover a range of statistical knowledge from basic concepts to advanced theoretical approaches.",
